			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blog.hafchurch.org/peter/index.php/2008/12/the-12-days-of-christmas-challenge/"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-303" title="The 12 Days of Christmas Challenge" src="http://blog.hafchurch.org/peter/wp-content/uploads/cooltext406950440-300x38.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="38" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://blog.hafchurch.org/peter/wp-content/bible.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-216" title="Bible Memorization" src="http://blog.hafchurch.org/peter/wp-content/bible-300x201.jpg" alt="" width="147" height="99" /></a>As I, my church and some of the wonderful readers here embark on the journey toward The 12 Days of Christmas Challenge, I thought that this week&#8217;s memory verse should be something to remind us of God&#8217;s promise to us when we pray.</p>
<p>When we pray, we can expect an answer. It&#8217;s as simple as that. Jesus said:</p>
<blockquote><p>Ask and it will be given to you; seek and you will find; knock and the door will be opened to you. (Matthew 7:7)</p></blockquote>
<p>So as you pray this week, wait for an answer, listen for the answer because the answer WILL come, maybe not exactly when you want it and maybe it won&#8217;t be exactly what you hoped it would be but the answer will come.</p>
<p>This is an easy one to memorize. See if you can have it and its reference committed to memory by the end of the week.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
